          "body": "2 Samuel 10 opens with a gesture that ought to have been unremarkable: a king extends covenant loyalty to the son of a deceased ally. The word the narrator uses — chesed (10:2) — is the same word used of God's covenant faithfulness in the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:15; cf. Ps 89:28). David is acting in character with his God. What transforms a diplomatic courtesy into a regional war is a single act of interpretation by the Ammonite princes (10:3): they read David's consolers as intelligence-gatherers, his kindness as cover for espionage. The narrator does not moralize; he simply reports the interpretation and its consequence — a calculated public shaming (10:4). The ancient Near Eastern significance of the act cannot be overstated. To shave half a man's beard and expose his body to his hips was to strip him of masculinity, social standing, and diplomatic immunity simultaneously. It was a declaration that David's envoys — and by extension David himself — were worthy only of contempt. Hanun's counselors turned chesed into a casus belli because they could not conceive of a king acting without ulterior motive. The chapter's opening tragedy is not military; it is hermeneutical: they could not read kindness as kindness."
