          "body": "The chapter's theological center is not David; it is Joab in verses 9-12. Faced with a genuine tactical crisis — enemy forces in front and behind simultaneously (10:9) — Joab does three things in sequence. First, he reads the battlefield with strategic clarity and divides his force to address both threats (10:9-10). Second, he establishes a mutual-aid covenant with his brother Abishai: 'if they are too strong for me, you shall help me; if too strong for you, I will come to help you' (10:11). Third, he delivers what amounts to a theological combat address: 'Be strong and courageous for the sake of our people and the cities of our God; and may the LORD do what is good in His sight' (10:12). The movement from strategy to solidarity to prayer is not coincidental. Joab understands that human competence and divine sovereignty are not competitors. He plans the best two-front deployment a commander can execute, coordinates mutual support, and then releases the outcome to the LORD. The phrase 'what is good in His sight' (*tov b'einav*) is the vocabulary of divine freedom — Joab does not presume to dictate the outcome he desires; he submits to the verdict of the God who sees. This is the chapter's sharpest theological moment, embedded in a military briefing, spoken by a commander not famous for piety. Chuck Swindoll notes the irony: Joab, the strategically ruthless general of 2 Samuel, articulates the most explicitly God-dependent statement in the chapter."
